      <section>
        <title>Government Bonds</title>
        <subtitle>A Question</subtitle>
        <chapter>
          <paragraph>
            The EU faces a tough political battle over changes to the regulatory treatment
            of government bonds. The issue has become a focus of political debate in recent
            months because of Germany’s insistence that the Euro area should reduce the
            risks banks are facing, including government debt on their balance sheets,
            before creating a common deposit insurance system to round out the so-called
            banking union. Here’s focal points of the question:
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <list type="unordered">
              <item>Finance ministers battled over the possibility of imposing limits on bank’s
              holdings of sovereign debt, with several member states opposing German.</item>
              <item>EU sovereign bonds are currently treated as risk-free and are exempt from exposure
              limits imposed on bank’s holdings of corporate or household debt.</item>
              <item>This privileged treatment has been seen from Germany as risky, especially when banks own too much
              debt issued by their own sovereign...</item>
              <item>...But some European countries have been
              cautious about backing change for fear of upsetting bond markets and banks’ financial stability.</item>
              <item>So, work will continue at the technical level and ministers may discuss the issue again in June,
              said Dutch finance minister Jeroen Dijsselbloem.</item>
            </list>
          </paragraph>
        </chapter>
